"""Errorz Barz -- precomputed step data for all 246 patterns, ready for
OAM Uncertainty.

(In the repo this file is named realized_patterns.py -- kept as
errorz_realized_patterns.py in this shared working folder to avoid
colliding with 68 Certain Teas' own realized_patterns.py sitting
alongside it.)

This is plain data -- no imports, no computation -- so it's meant to
live on the device itself alongside code.py. Everything below is
self-contained since gate_mapping.py and patterns.py (which generated
this file) don't ship to the microcontroller.

STEP_DATA is one flat `bytes` object rather than any nested Python
structure (no per-pattern dicts, no per-step tuples) -- that choice
came from a real MemoryError on hardware. The RP2040 doesn't precompile
.py files; it compiles them into bytecode at import time, and building
several thousand small nested list/tuple/int literals took enough
scratch memory to crash on boot, independent of how small the final
data ended up being. A single bytes literal is one token to the
compiler -- it gets copied in directly, no per-element parsing or
object construction. Each byte is a bitmask: bit (channel - 1) set
means that channel (1-8) fires on that step. code.py unpacks a step's
byte with plain bit tests; no tuple ever gets built there either.

Channel assignment and play order are both decided in gate_mapping.py
and baked into this file's layout -- see that file's docstring for the
full reasoning behind the fixed 8-channel layout and the style-grouped
play order (House, other EDM, Rock, Breaks, regional styles, then
everything else).

TERMS
    pattern    A single 16-step drum sequence -- steps
               STEP_DATA[p*16 : p*16+16] for pattern index p.
    step       One 16th of the measure. Every pattern here is exactly
               16 steps.
    channel    Which of Uncertainty's 8 gate outputs fires for a given
               step, encoded as bit (channel - 1) of that step's byte
               -- see gate_mapping.py for the fixed instrument-to-
               channel table, and patterns.py for the original per-
               pattern name/variant/instrument data if you need it for
               reference -- neither ships to the device.

STEP_DATA
    A single bytes object, PATTERN_COUNT * STEPS_PER_PATTERN long,
    grouped by style and then simplest-first within each style (see
    gate_mapping.py's PLAY_ORDER for exactly how). STEP_DATA[p *
    STEPS_PER_PATTERN + s] is pattern p's step s, as an 8-bit channel
    bitmask (0 = silent).

Source: Paul Wenzel, "Pocket Operations" (Second Edition, Rev. 3.1,
        2024). (c) 2024 Paul Wenzel, some rights reserved -- intended
        for educational use; see this project's README for the exact
        wording. Free copies at https://shittyrecording.studio
Built by: Claude (Sonnet) & cubbs, 2026.
"""

PATTERN_COUNT = 246
STEPS_PER_PATTERN = 16

